div.div:
Lies around the truth connection, which might seem true because of false truth structures like 'containing variation' or 'intersecting with the truth at one point' or being 'adjacent to the truth'.
The 'opposing forces that reverse/change these lies' are changes to offset the reason its a lie (the reason the 'adjacent straight line' is a lie is its position, so a vector to 'change its position' would offset the lie. These 'opposing structures' of a 'reason why a structure is a lie' are useful to apply to identify or create truths.
For example, the multi-angle lie might seem more true than the true straight line, which could seem too simple to be true, where the higher variation lie might seem more true because it applies a false truth structure (anything can be varied, but that doesn't make it true even though reality is likely to be high variation).

div.div:
A set of vertexes that when identified as "positioned adjacently with an overlap", can identify another structure, like whether there are other vertexes at similarly conversions of position (like repetitions of 60 degree angles around the clock).
Once the full set is identified, the generative variables can be identified (the center, the magnitudes of the vertexes, and the rotations that would generate them all).
Once the generative variables are identified, the structure is basically known (minus a few interactions that might also be useful to know as well), so the similarity between these vertexes might be better represented as a point, as once known, most structures start to be over-used and decay in value and structure, as higher variation structures are built using them.
Once the set is represented accurately as a point (such as a point on a graph of different sets of generators/origins), it may as well be non-existent, except in its relation to other points, which may be used more than it. This graph will likely also be reduced to a point, at which point each point on the graph may as well have never existed. This is a reality of 'interaction layers', where the new 'interaction layer' is the place where all variation moves and occurs, until a new one develops.
Some vertexes will resist this type of usage structure leading to uselessness, for a longer period of time than other vertexes, but ultimately vertexes themselves may become irrelevant on some interaction layer that is possible and will be traversed (reduced to a point which may as well be nonexistence).
Moving in a sequence towards 'higher variation interaction layers' is a way to allow time to happen non-sequentially. In an interaction layer where 'all sequences are equally possible or adjacent', sequences wouldn't be definitively real as in 'impacting reality' anymore (same for co-occurring sets, interactivities, probabilities and other structures that can cover reality).
